Design a E/R Model using crow's foot notation for a grade-keeping system described like the following:

Attributes:
- each student has a unique ID and name âœ…
- a course has a number (unique) and a title âœ…
- each assessment is identified by a number, a title and a type (quiz, homework, project, exam) âœ…

- students enroll in courses 1 - M <==> [1] -> [0..N]
- students can enroll in multiple courses M - M <==> [0..N] -> [0..N]
- a course can have multiple students 1 - M <==> [1] -> [0..N]

End result is that:
Students[0..N] -> Courses[0..N]

- Critical Entities:
    - Students âœ…
    - Courses âœ…
    - Assignments âœ…

- Scenario(s):
    - a course can have several assignments 1 to M <==> [1] -> [0..N]
    - each student receives a grade (0-10) for each assignment
*/

entity Students {
    id key
    name
}

entity Courses {
    number key
    title
}

entity Assignments {
    number key 
    title
    type // (quiz, homework, project, exam)
}

// STUDENTS ########################################
relationship enrolls {
/*
    Rel: Students can enroll in multiple courses (M-to-M) (ðŸ”¥)
    Students can enroll in multiple courses -> A course can have either 0 or many students.

    Explanation: 
    CASE 1 âœ…: Students can enroll in more than 1 course, and a course can have potentially many students enrolled. Students[N] -> Courses[N].

    CASE 2 âœ…: A Student can enroll in no courses (semester off) -> A course can have no students (new course). Students[0..N] -> Courses[0..N]
*/
    Students[0..N] -> Courses[0..N] // Optional
}

// COURSES ########################################
relationship contains {
    /*
    Rel: A course can have several assignments (1-to-M) (ðŸ”¥)

    Explanation:
    Assume that a course contains many assignments, and a assignment can only be associated with one course. Courses[1] -> Assignments[N]

    Determine if optional or mandatory:
    CASE 1 âœ…: A course can have no assignments (new course with no assignments), and either none or many assignment can be associated with one and only one course. Courses[1] -> Assignments[0..N]

    CASE 2 âœ…: A course must have at least one assignment (every course has at least one assignment), and each assignment is associated with one and only one course.

    CASE 3 âŒ: A course can have no assignments (new course with no assignments), Many assignments cannot be associated with no course (doesnt make sense).

    CASE 4 âŒ: A course must have exactly one assignment (every course has exactly one assignment), and each assignment is associated with one course. (Very restrictive and not practical for real world use cases.)

    */
    Courses[1] -> Assignments[0..N]
}


relationship receives {
    /*
     Rel: each student receives a grade (0-10) for each assignment.

    Explanation:
    Each student receives a grade for each assignment. Students[N] -> Assignments[N | "Graded 0 - 10" ]

    Determine if optional or mandatory:
    CASE 1 âŒ: A student can have no assignments that are graded (new student or joined class late), but many assignment cannot be associated with no students (doesnt make sense).

    CASE 2 âœ…: A student can have no assignments that are graded (new student or joined class late), and many assignment can be associated with one and only 1 student. Students[1] -> Assignments[0..N]
    */

    Students[1] -> Assignments[0..N | "Grades 0 - 10" ]
    grade
}



